Module 28 – Filing as Pattern Evidence 📊📄

Core Message

Your filings can be more than advocacy — they can document procedural injustice for future use.

⸻

Lesson Introduction

A consistent record of procedural irregularities can become evidence in later cases, policy advocacy, or public reporting.

⸻

Teaching Block

1. File with Dual Purpose
	•	Advocate for your case while documenting the irregularity.

2. Use Consistent Language
	•	Makes patterns easier to spot later.

3. Archive Everything
	•	Save all filings in organized form.

⸻

Real-World Illustration

Repeated filings documenting delayed docketing became exhibits in a later §1983 case.

⸻

Assignment Prompt

Task:
Identify one procedural injustice and draft how you’d document it in a motion.

⸻

Model Answer (Sample)

“This motion notes that the TRO filed July 1, 2025, was not docketed until July 14, 2025, without explanation, constituting procedural delay.”

⸻

Reflection Summary

Every filing can be a data point.

⸻

Visual Pairing

Image Concept:
A graph line rising with each filing date, labeled “Pattern Evidence.” Caption:
“Build the Pattern as You Litigate.”
